{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}} {{Use British English|date=June 2019}} {{Infobox UK legislation |short_title = War Crimes Act 1991 |type = Act |parliament = |long_title = An Act to confer jurisdiction on United Kingdom courts in respect of certain grave violations of the laws and customs of war committed in German-held territory during the Second World War; and for connected purposes. |year = 1991 |citation = 1991 c. 13 |introduced_by = |territorial_extent = United Kingdom |royal_assent = 9 May 1991 |commencement = |repeal_date = |replaces = |amends = |amendments = |related_legislation = |repealing_legislation= |status = Amended |original_text = |legislation_history = |use_new_UK-LEG = yes |UK-LEG_title = |revised_text = |theyworkforyou = |millbankhansard = }}
The '''War Crimes Act 1991''' is an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. It confers jurisdiction on courts in the [[United Kingdom]] to try people for [[war crimes]] committed in [[Nazi Germany]] or German-occupied territory during the [[World War II|Second World War]] by people who were not British citizens at the time, but have since become British citizens or residents. The legislation was enacted, as there then were no provisions to allow the extradition of [[British resident]]s, or [[naturalised citizen]]s to face trial for war crimes in third countries.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/274989.stm Prosecution prepares war crimes trial] ''[[BBC News]], [[news.bbc.co.uk]]'', 8 February 1999 (accessed 10 January 2009)</ref> Other countries, such as the [[United States]] have used [[Civil law (common law)|civil]], rather than [[criminal law|criminal]] proceedings, to resolve this issue by revoking citizenship of suspects, facilitating their deportation.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1525553.stm Unhappy record on Nazi suspects] ''[[BBC News]], [[news.bbc.co.uk]]'', 8 February 1999 (accessed 10 January 2009).</ref>
The Act was rejected by the [[House of Lords]], and so it was passed with the authority of only the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], under the provisions of the [[Parliament Acts 1911 and 1949]]. The Parliament Acts are rarely invoked: the War Crimes Act was only the fourth statute since 1911 enacted under their provisions, and the first since the Parliament Act 1949.<ref>{{cite hansard|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2010-04-08a.462.0|house=House of Lords|date=8 April 2010|column=462-463|title=Parliament Acts: House of Lords written question – answered on 8th April 2010.}}</ref> The War Crimes Act remains the only time that the Parliament Acts were invoked by a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government.
To date only one person, [[Anthony Sawoniuk]], has been convicted under the Act. In 1999, he was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] for [[murder]] during his involvement with the collaborationist [[Belarusian Auxiliary Police]]. He died in jail in 2005.
The first person to be charged, however, was fellow Belarusian officer, Symon Serafinowicz Sr. His trial commenced in 1997 for the murder of three unnamed Jews committed as during his role as Police chief in [[Mir, Belarus|Mir]]. At this stage, he was in the advanced stages of dementia and was declared medically unfit. He died later that year.
