in occupied Eastern and Central Germany, and against ethnic-German populations of Poland, Czechoslovakia, Hungary and Jugoslavia. The number of civilian victims in the years 1944–46 is estimated in at least 300,000, not all victims of war crimes; many died from starvation, cold weather and diseases.{{r|Ka-Lu2007_1001|Hitchcock03|deZayas94|Walter97}} |- |[[Treuenbrietzen]] ||War crimes || ||Following the capture of the German city of Treuenbrietzen after fierce fighting. Over a period of several days at the end of April and beginning of May roughly 1000 inhabitants of the city, most of them men, were executed by Soviet troops.<ref>Claus-Dieter Steyer, [https://archive.today/20120527030925/http://www.tagesspiegel.de/berlin/archiv/21.06.2006/2610181.asp "Stadt ohne Männer"] ("City without men"), ''[[Der Tagesspiegel]]'' online June 21, 2006; viewed November 11, 2006.</ref> |- ||[[Rape during the Soviet occupation of Poland (1944–1947)]] ||War crimes (mass rape) || ||Joanna Ostrowska and Marcin Zaremba of the [[Polish Academy of Sciences]] wrote that rapes of the [[Poles|Polish]] women reached a mass scale during the [[Red Army]]'s [[Vistula–Oder Offensive|Winter Offensive]] of 1945.<ref name="polityka">{{cite web | url=http://archiwum.polityka.pl/art/kobieca-gehenna,353703.html | title="Kobieca gehenna" (The women's ordeal) | publisher=[[Polityka]] | work=No 10 (2695) | date=2009-03-07 | accessdate=April 21, 2011 | author=Joanna Ostrowska, Marcin Zaremba | pages=64–66 | language=pl }}&nbsp; <br />[http://www.ihuw.pl/biogramy/index.php?UID=87 Dr. Marcin Zaremba] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007025551/http://www.ihuw.pl/biogramy/index.php?UID=87 |date=2011-10-07 }} of [[Polish Academy of Sciences]], the co-author of the article cited above – is a historian from [[Warsaw University]] Department of History Institute of 20th Century History ([https://scholar.google.ca/scholar?hl=en&q=%22Marcin+Zaremba%22&btnG=Search&as_sdt=0%2C5&as_ylo=&as_vis=0 cited 1