{{short description|Foundation}} {{More citations needed|date=August 2019}}
The '''Alfried Krupp von Bohlen und Halbach Foundation''' ({{lang-de|Alfried Krupp von Bohlen und Halbach-Stiftung}}) is a major German philanthropic foundation, created by and named in honour of [[Alfried Krupp von Bohlen und Halbach]], a convicted [[Crimes against humanity|criminal against humanity]],<ref>[https://archive.is/20130113055713/http://www.mazal.org/archive/nmt/09/NMT09-C001.htm#selection-141.0-141.15 The Krupp Case. Nuerenberg Military Tribunal, Vol 9]</ref> and the former owner and head of the [[Krupp]] company. Once it was the largest company in Europe, and one of largest [[World War II|wartime]] users of [[Forced labour under German rule during World War II|slave labor]]{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}} in [[Nazi Germany]], including the Krupp munitions factory (''Weichsel Union Metallwerke'') in the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz death camp]].<ref>[http://www.hist-chron.com/judentum-aktenlage/hol/Pressac_auschwitz-original-fotos-bauten-d/012-waffenfabrik-Krupp.jpg Index of /judentum-aktenlage]</ref> In 1959, the company promised to pay individual compensations of DM5,000 ($1,190) to 2,000 slave workers (or 2% of all the estimated estimated 100,000 slave workers), or DM10,000,000 ($2,380,000) in total.<ref>Theodore Shabad. 1959. Krupp Will Pay Slave Laborers: Jews Forced to Work in His Plants in World War II to Get $1,190 Each (p 1). ''The New York Times''. 24 Dec.</ref>
On the death of Alfried Krupp von Bohlen und Halbach in 1967,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.krupp-stiftung.de/historie/|title=Historie - Alfried Krupp von Bohlen und Halbach-Stiftung|publisher=|accessdate=13 September 2017}}</ref> the entire holdings of the Krupp family were transferred to the foundation. Today, the foundation is the largest shareholder of the [[ThyssenKrupp]] industrial conglomerate (20.9% as of 2018) and largely controls the board of the company. The foundation is also tasked with preserving the “unity” of ThyssenKrupp and uses proceeds from ThyssenKrupp’s dividend payments to further good causes in science and education.<ref>Tom Kaeckenhoff, Arno Schuetze and Edward Taylor (July 17, 2018), [https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thyssenkrupp-chairman-investors-expla/thyssenkrupps-foundation-to-steer-conglomerate-in-leadership-crisis-idUSKBN1K71VN Thyssenkrupp's foundation to steer conglomerate in leadership crisis] ''[[Reuters]]''.</ref> In the 2018 money, the aforementioned 1959 compensation payouts equate to $20,537,000, that is, €18,401,000. The sum is 0.02 percent of ThysenKrupp's 2018 assets, net income and equity, or over €72billion.<ref>[https://www.thyssenkrupp.com/media/investoren/berichterstattung_publikationen/update_21_11_2018/thyssenkrupp_ag_ar_2017_2018_eng_web.pdf ThyssenKrupp Annual Report 2017-2018. 2018.]</ref>{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}
